<TITLE> Speaker claims neutrality between AL and BNP </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Shehabuddin Kislu from New York New York, Apr 22 (bdnews24.com)  Abdul Hamid, the speaker of parliament, said that the role of the opposition in parliament is significant because only it can point out the mistakes of the government. He asked the opposition to play an active role in parliamentary debates. The speaker claimed that he was neutral and said that he gave the opposition sufficient time to speak in the House. The opposition however has claimed that it is rarely allowed to speak in parliament.. Hamid was speaking at a meeting on "Democracy and Development in Bangladesh" in New York on Wednesday. "Nobody can boycott parliament, claiming that they are not allowed to speak as long as speaker Abdul Hamid lives," he said. He said that former BNP speaker Jamiruddin Sircar allowed the Awami League, to speak for just one fifth of the total parliamentary time  equivalent to the proportion of parliamentary seats held by the AL. "But I never told the opposition that they will be only allowed to speak for one tenth of the total time," he said. He was alluding to the fact that the BNP has half the seats the AL had when it was in opposition. Between, 2001 and 2006, the Awami League had 58 members of parliament, and the BNP now has 30. Hamid said: "I always ensure that the opposition can speak. This is democracy." "If anybody boycotts parliament for political motivation I can not be blamed for that," he said. The United Nations Bangladesh Mission and the Global Non-resident Bangladeshi jointly organised the meetin
